==Range and habitat==
It breeds on [[Prince Edward Islands]], the [[Crozet Islands]], [[Kerguelen Island]], [[Amsterdam Island]] and [[<U+00CE>le Saint-Paul|St Paul Island]]s in the [[Indian Ocean]]. When feeding during incubation, birds will forage up to {{convert|1500|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the colony.<ref name="Pinaud">Pinaud D. & Weimerskirch, H. (2007)</ref> At sea it ranges from [[South Africa]] to the [[Pacific Ocean]] just beyond [[New Zealand]], ranging from 30<U+00B0> S to 50<U+00B0> S.<ref name="BLI" /><ref name="Harrison">Harrison P. (1983)</ref>
 
==Conservation==
It is considered to be an [[endangered species]] by the [[IUCN]],<ref name="IUCN" /> due to dramatic declines in the last seventy years, caused by interactions with [[longline fishing|longline fisheries]] and the outbreak of introduced [[disease]]s, such as [[Avian Cholera]] and [[Erysipelothrix rhusiopathidae]].<ref name="Ryan">Ryan, P. G. et al. (2002)</ref>
It has an occurrence range of {{convert|35300000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and a breeding range of {{convert|1400|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. A 2004 population estimate established that around a total of 65,000 adult birds are alive. This is based on earlier counts as follows: 27,000 breeding pairs breed on [[Amsterdam Island]],<ref name="Weimerskirch">Weimerskirch, H. (2008)</ref> and 7,500 pair on [[Prince Edward Island]],<ref name="Ryan" /> 7,030 on [[Crozet Island]],<ref name="ACAP">ACAP (2007)</ref> 50 on [[Kerguelen Island]],<ref name="WJ">Weimerskirch, H. & Jouventin P. (1998)</ref> and 3 pair on [[<U+00CE>le Saint-Paul|St. Paul Island]] for a total of 41,580 pair or 83,000 mature individuals. Take into account decreasing trends for the stated number.

Monitoring of the birds and studying of its foraging is an ongoing project on [[Amsterdam Island]], and [[Prince Edward Island]] is a nature preserve. A vaccination has been developed but remains untested.<ref name="Ryan" /> Finally, in 2006, the [[Indian Ocean Tuna Commission]] adopted a measure to require [[longline fishing|longline]] boats to use a bird streamer south of 30<U+00B0>S, and [[South Africa]] requires its boats to use a variety of mitigation processes.<ref name="BLI" />

==Etymology==
The binomial commemorates the English ornithologist [[Thomas Carter]].

